<br>
It is not up to the goverment to report the value of a company, regardless if they have inside information.  It amazes me that Bush goes and does the right thing and people still want to blame him and not Ken Lay or Jeff Skilling or Arthur Andersen.   Democrats are grasping for anything at all.  Imagine if Bush had done something...Democrats would be ALL over that, and let me tell ya, that'd be one hell of a scandal for Bush moreso than Ken Lay.<br>
<br>
I met Ken Lay in a meeting after EOG was sold off and I was doing desktop support for Enron Corp.  I also fixed a few issues he was having with his laptop.  He was a nice, so was his secretary, he was a very likable guy, but that doesn't excuse him from hiding secret partnerships and failing subsidiaries.  And it certainly doesn't mean Bush had anything to do with it.  <br>
<br>
Let me repeat, it is up to the company to report earnings, not the government.  If Bush got up there and said something bad about any company regardless if it was or wasn't doing well, it would cause a horrific and massive fluctuation in the stock market and companies that weren't even on the verge of bankruptcies to colapse.  It is a matter of national security that the President's administration remain quiet and as uninvolved as possible except in the area of dealing justice.<br>
